79/** Get the pure arguments. */
80std::vector<Var> Func::args() const {
81 const std::vector<std::string> arg_names = func.args();
82 std::vector<Var> args;
83 args.reserve(arg_names.size());
84 for (const auto &arg_name : arg_names) {
85 args.emplace_back(arg_name);
86 }
87 return args;

90/** The right-hand-side value of the pure definition of this
91 * function. An error if the Func has no definition, or is defined as
92 * a Tuple. */
93Expr Func::value() const {
94 user_assert(defined())
95 << "Can't call Func::value() on an undefined Func. To check if a Func is defined, call Func::defined()\n";
96 user_assert(func.outputs() == 1)
97 << "Can't call Func::value() on Func \"" << name() << "\", because it has multiple values.\n";
98 return func.values()[0];

143/** Get the RVars of the reduction domain for the update definition. Returns an
144 * empty vector if there's no update definition, or if the update definition has
145 * no domain. Note that the RVars returned are floating RVars, i.e. they don't
146 * actually have pointer to the reduction domain. */
147vector<RVar> Func::rvars(int idx) const {
148 user_assert(has_update_definition())
149 << "Can't call Func::update_args() on Func \"" << name() << "\" as it has no update definition. "
150 << "Use Func::has_update_definition() to check for the existence of an update definition.\n";
151 user_assert(idx < num_update_definitions())
152 << "Update definition index out of bounds.\n";
153 const std::vector<ReductionVariable> rvars = func.update(idx).schedule().rvars();
154 std::vector<RVar> rvs(rvars.size());
155 for (size_t i = 0; i < rvars.size(); i++) {
156 rvs[i] = RVar(rvars[i].var);
157 }
158 return rvs;

225std::pair<int, int> Func::add_implicit_vars(vector<Var> &args) const {
226 int placeholder_pos = -1;
227 int count = 0;
228 std::vector<Var>::iterator iter = args.begin();
229
230 while (iter != args.end() && !iter->same_as(_)) {
231 iter++;
232 }
233 if (iter != args.end()) {
234 placeholder_pos = (int)(iter - args.begin());
235 int i = 0;
236 iter = args.erase(iter);
237 while ((int)args.size() < dimensions()) {
238 Internal::debug(2) << "Adding implicit var " << i << " to call to " << name() << "\n";
239 iter = args.insert(iter, Var::implicit(i++));
240 iter++;
241 count++;
242 }
243 }
244
245 if (defined() && args.size() != (size_t)dimensions()) {
246 user_error << "Func \"" << name() << "\" was called with "
247 << args.size() << " arguments, but was defined with " << dimensions() << "\n";
248 }
249
250 return {placeholder_pos, count};
251}
252
253std::pair<int, int> Func::add_implicit_vars(vector<Expr> &args) const {
254 int placeholder_pos = -1;
255 int count = 0;
256 std::vector<Expr>::iterator iter = args.begin();
257 while (iter != args.end()) {
258 const Variable *var = iter->as<Variable>();
259 if (var && var->name == Var(_).name()) {
260 break;
261 }
262 iter++;
263 }
264 if (iter != args.end()) {
265 placeholder_pos = (int)(iter - args.begin());
266 int i = 0;
267 iter = args.erase(iter);
268 while ((int)args.size() < dimensions()) {
269 Internal::debug(2) << "Adding implicit var " << i << " to call to " << name() << "\n";
270 iter = args.insert(iter, Var::implicit(i++));
271 iter++;
272 count++;
273 }
274 }
275
276 if (defined() && args.size() != (size_t)dimensions()) {
277 user_error << "Func \"" << name() << "\" was called with "
278 << args.size() << " arguments, but was defined with " << dimensions() << "\n";
279 }
280
281 return {placeholder_pos, count};
282}

285bool var_name_match(const string &candidate, const string &var) {
286 internal_assert(var.find('.') == string::npos)
287 << "var_name_match expects unqualified names for the second argument. "
288 << "Name passed: " << var << "\n";
289 if (candidate == var) {
290 return true;
291 }
292 return Internal::ends_with(candidate, "." + var);
293}

301namespace {
302bool is_const_assignment(const string &func_name, const vector<Expr> &args, const vector<Expr> &values) {
303 // Check if an update definition is a non-recursive and just
304 // scatters a value that doesn't depend on the reduction
305 // domain. Such definitions can be treated the same as
306 // associative/commutative ones. I.e. we can safely split/reorder:
307 // f(g(r)) = 4;
308
309 // More generally, any value that does not recursively load the
310 // func or use the rvar on the RHS is also fine, because there can
311 // never be races between two distinct values of the pure var by
312 // construction (because the pure var must appear as one of the
313 // args) e.g: f(g(r, x), x) = h(x);
314 class Checker : public IRVisitor {
315 using IRVisitor::visit;
316
317 void visit(const Variable *op) override {
318 has_rvar |= op->reduction_domain.defined();
319 }
320
321 void visit(const Call *op) override {
322 has_self_reference |= (op->call_type == Call::Halide && op->name == func_name);
323 IRVisitor::visit(op);
324 }
325
326 const string &func_name;
327
328 public:
329 Checker(const string &func_name)
330 : func_name(func_name) {
331 }
332
333 bool has_self_reference = false;
334 bool has_rvar = false;
335 } lhs_checker(func_name), rhs_checker(func_name);
336 for (const Expr &v : args) {
337 v.accept(&lhs_checker);
338 }
339 for (const Expr &v : values) {
340 v.accept(&rhs_checker);
341 }
342 return !(lhs_checker.has_self_reference ||
343 rhs_checker.has_self_reference ||
344 rhs_checker.has_rvar);
345}

348void Stage::set_dim_type(const VarOrRVar &var, ForType t) {
349 bool found = false;
350 vector<Dim> &dims = definition.schedule().dims();
351 for (size_t i = 0; i < dims.size(); i++) {
352 if (var_name_match(dims[i].var, var.name())) {
353 found = true;
354 dims[i].for_type = t;
355
356 // If it's an rvar and the for type is parallel, we need to
357 // validate that this doesn't introduce a race condition,
358 // unless it is flagged explicitly or is a associative atomic operation.
359 if (!dims[i].is_pure() && var.is_rvar && is_parallel(t)) {
360 if (!definition.schedule().allow_race_conditions() &&
361 definition.schedule().atomic()) {
362 if (!definition.schedule().override_atomic_associativity_test()) {
363 // We only allow allow associative atomic operations
364 const string &func_name = function.name();
365 vector<Expr> &args = definition.args();
366 vector<Expr> &values = definition.values();
367
368 if (!is_const_assignment(func_name, args, values)) {
369 // Check whether the operator is associative and determine the operator and
370 // its identity for each value in the definition if it is a Tuple
371 const auto &prover_result = prove_associativity(func_name, args, values);
372
373 user_assert(prover_result.associative())
374 << "Failed to call atomic() on " << name()
375 << " since it can't prove associativity of the operator.\n";
376 internal_assert(prover_result.size() == values.size());
377 }
378 }
379 }
380 user_assert(definition.schedule().allow_race_conditions() ||
381 definition.schedule().atomic())
382 << "In schedule for " << name()
383 << ", marking var " << var.name()
384 << " as parallel or vectorized may introduce a race"
385 << " condition resulting in incorrect output."
386 << " It is possible to parallelize this by using the"
387 << " atomic() method if the operation is associative,"
388 << " or set override_associativity_test to true in the atomic method "
389 << " if you are certain that the operation is associative."
390 << " It is also possible to override this error using"
391 << " the allow_race_conditions() method. Use allow_race_conditions()"
392 << " with great caution, and only when you are willing"
393 << " to accept non-deterministic output, or you can prove"
394 << " that any race conditions in this code do not change"
395 << " the output, or you can prove that there are actually"
396 << " no race conditions, and that Halide is being too cautious.\n";
397 }
398 }
399 }
400
401 if (!found) {
402 user_error << "In schedule for " << name()
403 << ", could not find dimension "
404 << var.name()
405 << " to mark as " << t
406 << " in vars for function\n"
407 << dump_argument_list();
408 }
409}

411void Stage::set_dim_device_api(const VarOrRVar &var, DeviceAPI device_api) {
412 bool found = false;
413 vector<Dim> &dims = definition.schedule().dims();
414 for (size_t i = 0; i < dims.size(); i++) {
415 if (var_name_match(dims[i].var, var.name())) {
416 found = true;
417 dims[i].device_api = device_api;
418 }
419 }
420
421 if (!found) {
422 user_error << "In schedule for " << name()
423 << ", could not find dimension "
424 << var.name()
425 << " to set to device API " << static_cast<int>(device_api)
426 << " in vars for function\n"
427 << dump_argument_list();
428 }

437class SubstituteSelfReference : public IRMutator {
438 using IRMutator::visit;
439
440 const string func;
441 const Function substitute;
442 const vector<Var> new_args;
443
444 Expr visit(const Call *c) override {
445 Expr expr = IRMutator::visit(c);
446 c = expr.as<Call>();
447 internal_assert(c);
448
449 if ((c->call_type == Call::Halide) && (func == c->name)) {
450 debug(4) << "...Replace call to Func \"" << c->name << "\" with "
451 << "\"" << substitute.name() << "\"\n";
452 vector<Expr> args;
453 args.insert(args.end(), c->args.begin(), c->args.end());
454 args.insert(args.end(), new_args.begin(), new_args.end());
455 expr = Call::make(substitute, args, c->value_index);
456 }
457 return expr;
458 }
459
460public:
461 SubstituteSelfReference(const string &func, const Function &substitute,
462 const vector<Var> &new_args)
463 : func(func), substitute(substitute), new_args(new_args) {
464 internal_assert(substitute.get_contents().defined());
465 }
466};
467
468/** Substitute all self-reference calls to 'func' with 'substitute' which
469 * args (LHS) is the old args (LHS) plus 'new_args' in that order.
470 * Expect this method to be called on the value (RHS) of an update definition. */
471Expr substitute_self_reference(Expr val, const string &func, const Function &substitute,
472 const vector<Var> &new_args) {
473 SubstituteSelfReference subs(func, substitute, new_args);
474 val = subs.mutate(val);
475 return val;
476}

478// Substitute the occurrence of 'name' in 'exprs' with 'value'.
479void substitute_var_in_exprs(const string &name, const Expr &value, vector<Expr> &exprs) {
480 for (auto &expr : exprs) {
481 expr = substitute(name, value, expr);
482 }

485void apply_split_result(const vector<pair<string, Expr>> &bounds_let_stmts,
486 const vector<ApplySplitResult> &splits_result,
487 vector<Expr> &predicates, vector<Expr> &args,
488 vector<Expr> &values) {
489
490 for (const auto &res : splits_result) {
491 if (res.is_substitution() || res.is_let()) {
492 // Apply substitutions to the list of predicates, args, and values.
493 // Make sure we substitute in all the let stmts as well since we are
494 // not going to add them to the exprs.
495 substitute_var_in_exprs(res.name, res.value, predicates);
496 substitute_var_in_exprs(res.name, res.value, args);
497 substitute_var_in_exprs(res.name, res.value, values);
498 } else {
499 internal_assert(res.is_predicate());
500 predicates.push_back(res.value);
501 }
502 }
503
504 // Make sure we substitute in all the let stmts from 'bounds_let_stmts'
505 // since we are not going to add them to the exprs.
506 for (const auto &let : bounds_let_stmts) {
507 substitute_var_in_exprs(let.first, let.second, predicates);
508 substitute_var_in_exprs(let.first, let.second, args);
509 substitute_var_in_exprs(let.first, let.second, values);
510 }
511}

513/** Apply split directives on the reduction variables. Remove the old RVar from
514 * the list and add the split result (inner and outer RVars) to the list. Add
515 * new predicates corresponding to the TailStrategy to the RDom predicate list. */
516bool apply_split(const Split &s, vector<ReductionVariable> &rvars,
517 vector<Expr> &predicates, vector<Expr> &args,
518 vector<Expr> &values, map<string, Expr> &dim_extent_alignment) {
519 internal_assert(s.is_split());
520 const auto it = std::find_if(rvars.begin(), rvars.end(),
521 [&s](const ReductionVariable &rv) { return (s.old_var == rv.var); });
522
523 Expr old_max, old_min, old_extent;
524
525 if (it != rvars.end()) {
526 debug(4) << " Splitting " << it->var << " into " << s.outer << " and " << s.inner << "\n";
527
528 old_max = simplify(it->min + it->extent - 1);
529 old_min = it->min;
530 old_extent = it->extent;
531
532 it->var = s.inner;
533 it->min = 0;
534 it->extent = s.factor;
535
536 rvars.insert(it + 1, {s.outer, 0, simplify((old_extent - 1 + s.factor) / s.factor)});
537
538 vector<ApplySplitResult> splits_result = apply_split(s, true, "", dim_extent_alignment);
539 vector<pair<string, Expr>> bounds_let_stmts = compute_loop_bounds_after_split(s, "");
540 apply_split_result(bounds_let_stmts, splits_result, predicates, args, values);
541
542 return true;
543 }
544 return false;
545}
546
547/** Apply fuse directives on the reduction variables. Remove the
548 * fused RVars from the list and add the fused RVar to the list. */
549bool apply_fuse(const Split &s, vector<ReductionVariable> &rvars,
550 vector<Expr> &predicates, vector<Expr> &args,
551 vector<Expr> &values, map<string, Expr> &dim_extent_alignment) {
552 internal_assert(s.is_fuse());
553 const auto &iter_outer = std::find_if(rvars.begin(), rvars.end(),
554 [&s](const ReductionVariable &rv) { return (s.outer == rv.var); });
555 const auto &iter_inner = std::find_if(rvars.begin(), rvars.end(),
556 [&s](const ReductionVariable &rv) { return (s.inner == rv.var); });
557
558 Expr inner_min, inner_extent, outer_min, outer_extent;
559 if ((iter_outer != rvars.end()) && (iter_inner != rvars.end())) {
560 debug(4) << " Fusing " << s.outer << " and " << s.inner << " into " << s.old_var << "\n";
561
562 inner_min = iter_inner->min;
563 inner_extent = iter_inner->extent;
564 outer_min = iter_outer->min;
565 outer_extent = iter_outer->extent;
566
567 Expr extent = iter_outer->extent * iter_inner->extent;
568 iter_outer->var = s.old_var;
569 iter_outer->min = 0;
570 iter_outer->extent = extent;
571 rvars.erase(iter_inner);
572
573 vector<ApplySplitResult> splits_result = apply_split(s, true, "", dim_extent_alignment);
574 vector<pair<string, Expr>> bounds_let_stmts = compute_loop_bounds_after_split(s, "");
575 apply_split_result(bounds_let_stmts, splits_result, predicates, args, values);
576
577 return true;
578 }
579 return false;
580}
581
582/** Apply purify directives on the reduction variables and predicates. Purify
583 * replace a RVar with a Var, thus, the RVar needs to be removed from the list.
584 * Any reference to the RVar in the predicates will be replaced with reference
585 * to a Var. */
586bool apply_purify(const Split &s, vector<ReductionVariable> &rvars,
587 vector<Expr> &predicates, vector<Expr> &args,
588 vector<Expr> &values, map<string, Expr> &dim_extent_alignment) {
589 internal_assert(s.is_purify());
590 const auto &iter = std::find_if(rvars.begin(), rvars.end(),
591 [&s](const ReductionVariable &rv) { return (s.old_var == rv.var); });
592 if (iter != rvars.end()) {
593 debug(4) << " Purify RVar " << iter->var << " into Var " << s.outer
594 << ", deleting it from the rvars list\n";
595 rvars.erase(iter);
596
597 vector<ApplySplitResult> splits_result = apply_split(s, true, "", dim_extent_alignment);
598 vector<pair<string, Expr>> bounds_let_stmts = compute_loop_bounds_after_split(s, "");
599 apply_split_result(bounds_let_stmts, splits_result, predicates, args, values);
600
601 return true;
602 }
603 return false;
604}
605
606/** Apply rename directives on the reduction variables. */
607bool apply_rename(const Split &s, vector<ReductionVariable> &rvars,
608 vector<Expr> &predicates, vector<Expr> &args,
609 vector<Expr> &values, map<string, Expr> &dim_extent_alignment) {
610 internal_assert(s.is_rename());
611 const auto &iter = std::find_if(rvars.begin(), rvars.end(),
612 [&s](const ReductionVariable &rv) { return (s.old_var == rv.var); });
613 if (iter != rvars.end()) {
614 debug(4) << " Renaming " << iter->var << " into " << s.outer << "\n";
615 iter->var = s.outer;
616
617 vector<ApplySplitResult> splits_result = apply_split(s, true, "", dim_extent_alignment);
618 vector<pair<string, Expr>> bounds_let_stmts = compute_loop_bounds_after_split(s, "");
619 apply_split_result(bounds_let_stmts, splits_result, predicates, args, values);
620
621 return true;
622 }
623 return false;
624}
625
626/** Apply scheduling directives (e.g. split, fuse, etc.) on the reduction
627 * variables. */
628bool apply_split_directive(const Split &s, vector<ReductionVariable> &rvars,
629 vector<Expr> &predicates, vector<Expr> &args,
630 vector<Expr> &values) {
631 map<string, Expr> dim_extent_alignment;
632 for (const ReductionVariable &rv : rvars) {
633 dim_extent_alignment[rv.var] = rv.extent;
634 }
635
636 vector<pair<string, Expr>> rvar_bounds;
637 for (const ReductionVariable &rv : rvars) {
638 rvar_bounds.emplace_back(rv.var + ".loop_min", rv.min);
639 rvar_bounds.emplace_back(rv.var + ".loop_max", simplify(rv.min + rv.extent - 1));
640 rvar_bounds.emplace_back(rv.var + ".loop_extent", rv.extent);
641 }
642
643 bool found = false;
644 if (s.is_split()) {
645 found = apply_split(s, rvars, predicates, args, values, dim_extent_alignment);
646 } else if (s.is_fuse()) {
647 found = apply_fuse(s, rvars, predicates, args, values, dim_extent_alignment);
648 } else if (s.is_purify()) {
649 found = apply_purify(s, rvars, predicates, args, values, dim_extent_alignment);
650 } else {
651 found = apply_rename(s, rvars, predicates, args, values, dim_extent_alignment);
652 }
653
654 if (found) {
655 for (const auto &let : rvar_bounds) {
656 substitute_var_in_exprs(let.first, let.second, predicates);
657 substitute_var_in_exprs(let.first, let.second, args);
658 substitute_var_in_exprs(let.first, let.second, values);
659 }
660 }
661 return found;
662}
663
664} // anonymous namespace
665
666Func Stage::rfactor(const RVar &r, const Var &v) {
667 return rfactor({{r, v}});
668}
669
670Func Stage::rfactor(vector<pair<RVar, Var>> preserved) {
671 user_assert(!definition.is_init()) << "rfactor() must be called on an update definition\n";
672
673 const string &func_name = function.name();
674 vector<Expr> &args = definition.args();
675 vector<Expr> &values = definition.values();
676
677 // Check whether the operator is associative and determine the operator and
678 // its identity for each value in the definition if it is a Tuple
679 const auto &prover_result = prove_associativity(func_name, args, values);
680
681 user_assert(prover_result.associative())
682 << "Failed to call rfactor() on " << name()
683 << " since it can't prove associativity of the operator\n";
684 internal_assert(prover_result.size() == values.size());
685
686 vector<Split> &splits = definition.schedule().splits();
687 vector<Dim> &dims = definition.schedule().dims();
688 vector<ReductionVariable> &rvars = definition.schedule().rvars();
689 vector<Expr> predicates = definition.split_predicate();
690
691 Scope<string> scope; // Contains list of RVars lifted to the intermediate Func
692 vector<string> rvars_removed;
693
694 vector<bool> is_rfactored(dims.size(), false);
695 for (const pair<RVar, Var> &i : preserved) {
696 const RVar &rv = i.first;
697 const Var &v = i.second;
698 {
699 // Check that the RVar are in the dims list
700 const auto &iter = std::find_if(dims.begin(), dims.end(),
701 [&rv](const Dim &dim) { return var_name_match(dim.var, rv.name()); });
702 user_assert((iter != dims.end()) && (*iter).is_rvar())
703 << "In schedule for " << name()
704 << ", can't perform rfactor() on " << rv.name()
705 << " since it is not in the reduction domain\n"
706 << dump_argument_list();
707 is_rfactored[iter - dims.begin()] = true;
708 }
709 {
710 // Check that the new pure Vars we used to rename the RVar aren't already in the dims list
711 const auto &iter = std::find_if(dims.begin(), dims.end(),
712 [&v](const Dim &dim) { return var_name_match(dim.var, v.name()); });
713 user_assert(iter == dims.end())
714 << "In schedule for " << name()
715 << ", can't rename the rvars " << rv.name() << " into " << v.name()
716 << ", since it is already used in this Func's schedule elsewhere.\n"
717 << dump_argument_list();
718 }
719 }
720
721 // If the operator is associative but non-commutative, rfactor() on inner
722 // dimensions (excluding the outer dimensions) is not valid.
723 if (!prover_result.commutative()) {
724 int last_rvar = -1;
725 for (int i = dims.size() - 1; i >= 0; --i) {
726 if ((last_rvar != -1) && is_rfactored[i]) {
727 user_assert(is_rfactored[last_rvar])
728 << "In schedule for " << name()
729 << ", can't rfactor an inner dimension " << dims[i].var
730 << " without rfactoring the outer dimensions, since the "
731 << "operator is non-commutative.\n"
732 << dump_argument_list();
733 }
734 if (dims[i].is_rvar()) {
735 last_rvar = i;
736 }
737 }
738 }
739
740 // We need to apply the split directives on the reduction vars, so that we can
741 // correctly lift the RVars not in 'rvars_kept' and distribute the RVars to the
742 // intermediate and merge Funcs.
743 {
744 vector<Split> temp;
745 for (const Split &s : splits) {
746 // If it's already applied, we should remove it from the split list.
747 if (!apply_split_directive(s, rvars, predicates, args, values)) {
748 temp.push_back(s);
749 }
750 }
751 splits = temp;
752 }
753
754 // Reduction domain of the intermediate update definition
755 vector<ReductionVariable> intm_rvars;
756 for (const auto &rv : rvars) {
757 const auto &iter = std::find_if(preserved.begin(), preserved.end(),
758 [&rv](const pair<RVar, Var> &pair) { return var_name_match(rv.var, pair.first.name()); });
759 if (iter == preserved.end()) {
760 intm_rvars.push_back(rv);
761 scope.push(rv.var, rv.var);
762 }
763 }
764 RDom intm_rdom(intm_rvars);
765
766 // Sort the Rvars kept and their Vars replacement based on the RVars of
767 // the reduction domain AFTER applying the split directives, so that we
768 // can have a consistent args order for the update definition of the
769 // intermediate and new merge Funcs.
770 std::sort(preserved.begin(), preserved.end(),
771 [&](const pair<RVar, Var> &lhs, const pair<RVar, Var> &rhs) {
772 const auto &iter_lhs = std::find_if(rvars.begin(), rvars.end(),
773 [&lhs](const ReductionVariable &rv) { return var_name_match(rv.var, lhs.first.name()); });
774 const auto &iter_rhs = std::find_if(rvars.begin(), rvars.end(),
775 [&rhs](const ReductionVariable &rv) { return var_name_match(rv.var, rhs.first.name()); });
776 return iter_lhs < iter_rhs;
777 });
778 // The list of RVars to keep in the new update definition
779 vector<RVar> rvars_kept(preserved.size());
780 // List of pure Vars to replace the RVars in the intermediate's update definition
781 vector<Var> vars_rename(preserved.size());
782 for (size_t i = 0; i < preserved.size(); ++i) {
783 const auto &val = preserved[i];
784 rvars_kept[i] = val.first;
785 vars_rename[i] = val.second;
786 }
787
788 // List of RVars for the new reduction domain. Any RVars not in 'rvars_kept'
789 // are removed from the RDom
790 {
791 vector<ReductionVariable> temp;
792 for (const auto &rv : rvars) {
793 const auto &iter = std::find_if(rvars_kept.begin(), rvars_kept.end(),
794 [&rv](const RVar &rvar) { return var_name_match(rv.var, rvar.name()); });
795 if (iter != rvars_kept.end()) {
796 temp.push_back(rv);
797 } else {
798 rvars_removed.push_back(rv.var);
799 }
800 }
801 rvars.swap(temp);
802 }
803 RDom f_rdom(rvars);
804
805 // Init definition of the intermediate Func
806
807 // Compute args of the init definition of the intermediate Func.
808 // Replace the RVars, which are in 'rvars_kept', with the specified new pure
809 // Vars. Also, add the pure Vars of the original init definition as part of
810 // the args.
811 // For example, if we have the following Func f:
812 // f(x, y) = 10
813 // f(r.x, r.y) += h(r.x, r.y)
814 // Calling f.update(0).rfactor({{r.y, u}}) will generate the following
815 // intermediate Func:
816 // f_intm(x, y, u) = 0
817 // f_intm(r.x, u, u) += h(r.x, u)
818
819 vector<Var> init_args;
820 init_args.insert(init_args.end(), dim_vars.begin(), dim_vars.end());
821 init_args.insert(init_args.end(), vars_rename.begin(), vars_rename.end());
822
823 vector<Expr> init_vals(values.size());
824 for (size_t i = 0; i < init_vals.size(); ++i) {
825 init_vals[i] = prover_result.pattern.identities[i];
826 }
827
828 Func intm(func_name + "_intm");
829 intm(init_args) = Tuple(init_vals);
830
831 // Args of the update definition of the intermediate Func
832 vector<Expr> update_args(args.size() + vars_rename.size());
833
834 // We need to substitute the reference to the old RDom's RVars with
835 // the new RDom's RVars. Also, substitute the reference to RVars which
836 // are in 'rvars_kept' with their corresponding new pure Vars
837 map<string, Expr> substitution_map;
838 for (size_t i = 0; i < intm_rvars.size(); ++i) {
839 substitution_map[intm_rvars[i].var] = intm_rdom[i];
840 }
841 for (size_t i = 0; i < vars_rename.size(); i++) {
842 update_args[i + args.size()] = vars_rename[i];
843 RVar rvar_kept = rvars_kept[i];
844 // Find the full name of rvar_kept in rvars
845 const auto &iter = std::find_if(rvars.begin(), rvars.end(),
846 [&rvar_kept](const ReductionVariable &rv) { return var_name_match(rv.var, rvar_kept.name()); });
847 substitution_map[iter->var] = vars_rename[i];
848 }
849 for (size_t i = 0; i < args.size(); i++) {
850 Expr arg = substitute(substitution_map, args[i]);
851 update_args[i] = arg;
852 }
853
854 // Compute the predicates for the intermediate Func and the new update definition
855 for (const Expr &pred : predicates) {
856 Expr subs_pred = substitute(substitution_map, pred);
857 intm_rdom.where(subs_pred);
858 if (!expr_uses_vars(pred, scope)) {
859 // Only keep the predicate that does not depend on the lifted RVars
860 // (either explicitly or implicitly). For example, if 'rx' is split
861 // into 'rxo' and 'rxi' and 'rxo' is part of the lifted RVars, we'll
862 // ignore every predicate that depends on 'rx'
863 f_rdom.where(pred);
864 }
865 }
866 definition.predicate() = f_rdom.domain().predicate();
867
868 // The update values the intermediate Func should compute
869 vector<Expr> update_vals(values.size());
870 for (size_t i = 0; i < update_vals.size(); i++) {
871 Expr val = substitute(substitution_map, values[i]);
872 // Need to update the self-reference in the update definition to point
873 // to the new intermediate Func
874 val = substitute_self_reference(val, func_name, intm.function(), vars_rename);
875 update_vals[i] = val;
876 }
877 intm(update_args) = Tuple(update_vals);
878
879 // Determine the dims and schedule of the update definition of the
880 // intermediate Func. We copy over the schedule from the original
881 // update definition (e.g. split, parallelize, vectorize, etc.)
882 intm.function().update(0).schedule().dims() = dims;
883 intm.function().update(0).schedule().splits() = splits;
884
885 // Copy over the storage order of the original pure dims
886 vector<StorageDim> &intm_storage_dims = intm.function().schedule().storage_dims();
887 internal_assert(intm_storage_dims.size() ==
888 function.schedule().storage_dims().size() + vars_rename.size());
889 for (size_t i = 0; i < function.schedule().storage_dims().size(); ++i) {
890 intm_storage_dims[i] = function.schedule().storage_dims()[i];
891 }
892
893 for (size_t i = 0; i < rvars_kept.size(); ++i) {
894 // Apply the purify directive that replaces the RVar in rvars_kept
895 // with a pure Var
896 intm.update(0).purify(rvars_kept[i], vars_rename[i]);
897 }
898
899 // Determine the dims of the new update definition
900
901 // Add pure Vars from the original init definition to the dims list
902 // if they are not already in the list
903 for (const Var &v : dim_vars) {
904 const auto &iter = std::find_if(dims.begin(), dims.end(),
905 [&v](const Dim &dim) { return var_name_match(dim.var, v.name()); });
906 if (iter == dims.end()) {
907 Dim d = {v.name(), ForType::Serial, DeviceAPI::None, DimType::PureVar};
908 dims.insert(dims.end() - 1, d);
909 }
910 }
911 // Then, we need to remove lifted RVars from the dims list
912 for (const string &rv : rvars_removed) {
913 remove(rv);
914 }
915
916 // Define the new update definition which refers to the intermediate Func.
917 // Using the same example as above, the new update definition is:
918 // f(x, y) += f_intm(x, y, r.y)
919
920 // Args for store in the new update definition
921 vector<Expr> f_store_args(dim_vars.size());
922 for (size_t i = 0; i < f_store_args.size(); ++i) {
923 f_store_args[i] = dim_vars[i];
924 }
925
926 // Call's args to the intermediate Func in the new update definition
927 vector<Expr> f_load_args;
928 f_load_args.insert(f_load_args.end(), dim_vars.begin(), dim_vars.end());
929 for (int i = 0; i < f_rdom.dimensions(); ++i) {
930 f_load_args.push_back(f_rdom[i]);
931 }
932 internal_assert(f_load_args.size() == init_args.size());
933
934 // Update value of the new update definition. It loads values from
935 // the intermediate Func.
936 vector<Expr> f_values(values.size());
937
938 // There might be cross-dependencies between tuple elements, so we need
939 // to collect all substitutions first.
940 map<string, Expr> replacements;
941 for (size_t i = 0; i < f_values.size(); ++i) {
942 if (!prover_result.ys[i].var.empty()) {
943 Expr r = (values.size() == 1) ? Expr(intm(f_load_args)) : Expr(intm(f_load_args)[i]);
944 replacements.emplace(prover_result.ys[i].var, r);
945 }
946
947 if (!prover_result.xs[i].var.empty()) {
948 Expr prev_val = Call::make(intm.output_types()[i], func_name,
949 f_store_args, Call::CallType::Halide,
950 FunctionPtr(), i);
951 replacements.emplace(prover_result.xs[i].var, prev_val);
952 } else {
953 user_warning << "Update definition of " << name() << " at index " << i
954 << " doesn't depend on the previous value. This isn't a"
955 << " reduction operation\n";
956 }
957 }
958 for (size_t i = 0; i < f_values.size(); ++i) {
959 f_values[i] = substitute(replacements, prover_result.pattern.ops[i]);
960 }
961
962 // Update the definition
963 args.swap(f_store_args);
964 values.swap(f_values);
965
966 return intm;
967}
968
969void Stage::split(const string &old, const string &outer, const string &inner, const Expr &factor, bool exact, TailStrategy tail) {
970 debug(4) << "In schedule for " << name() << ", split " << old << " into "
971 << outer << " and " << inner << " with factor of " << factor << "\n";
972 vector<Dim> &dims = definition.schedule().dims();
973
974 // Check that the new names aren't already in the dims list.
975 for (size_t i = 0; i < dims.size(); i++) {
976 string new_names[2] = {inner, outer};
977 for (int j = 0; j < 2; j++) {
978 if (var_name_match(dims[i].var, new_names[j]) && new_names[j] != old) {
979 user_error << "In schedule for " << name()
980 << ", can't create var " << new_names[j]
981 << " using a split or tile, because " << new_names[j]
982 << " is already used in this Func's schedule elsewhere.\n"
983 << dump_argument_list();
984 }
985 }
986 }
987
988 // Replace the old dimension with the new dimensions in the dims list
989 bool found = false;
990 string inner_name, outer_name, old_name;
991
992 for (size_t i = 0; (!found) && i < dims.size(); i++) {
993 if (var_name_match(dims[i].var, old)) {
994 found = true;
995 old_name = dims[i].var;
996 inner_name = old_name + "." + inner;
997 outer_name = old_name + "." + outer;
998 dims.insert(dims.begin() + i, dims[i]);
999 dims[i].var = inner_name;
1000 dims[i + 1].var = outer_name;
1001 if (dims[i].for_type == ForType::Extern) {
1002 // If we split an extern loop, mark the outer loop serial.
1003 dims[i + 1].for_type = ForType::Serial;
1004 }
1005 }
1006 }
1007
1008 if (!found) {
1009 user_error << "In schedule for " << name()
1010 << ", could not find split dimension: "
1011 << old
1012 << "\n"
1013 << dump_argument_list();
1014 }
1015
1016 bool round_up_ok = !exact;
1017 if (round_up_ok && !definition.is_init()) {
1018 // If it's the outermost split in this dimension, RoundUp
1019 // is OK. Otherwise we need GuardWithIf to avoid
1020 // recomputing values in the case where the inner split
1021 // factor does not divide the outer split factor.
1022 std::set<string> inner_vars;
1023 for (const Split &s : definition.schedule().splits()) {
1024 if (s.is_split()) {
1025 inner_vars.insert(s.inner);
1026 if (inner_vars.count(s.old_var)) {
1027 inner_vars.insert(s.outer);
1028 }
1029 } else if (s.is_rename() || s.is_purify()) {
1030 if (inner_vars.count(s.old_var)) {
1031 inner_vars.insert(s.outer);
1032 }
1033 } else if (s.is_fuse()) {
1034 if (inner_vars.count(s.inner) || inner_vars.count(s.outer)) {
1035 inner_vars.insert(s.old_var);
1036 }
1037 }
1038 }
1039 round_up_ok = !inner_vars.count(old_name);
1040 user_assert(round_up_ok || tail != TailStrategy::RoundUp)
1041 << "Can't use TailStrategy::RoundUp for splitting " << old_name
1042 << " in update definition of " << name() << ". "
1043 << "It may redundantly recompute some values, which "
1044 << "could change the meaning of the algorithm. "
1045 << "Use TailStrategy::GuardWithIf instead.";
1046 }
1047
1048 if (tail == TailStrategy::Auto) {
1049 // Select a tail strategy
1050 if (exact) {
1051 tail = TailStrategy::GuardWithIf;
1052 } else if (!definition.is_init()) {
1053 tail = round_up_ok ? TailStrategy::RoundUp : TailStrategy::GuardWithIf;
1054 } else {
1055 // We should employ ShiftInwards when we can to prevent
1056 // overcompute and adding constraints to the bounds of
1057 // inputs and outputs. However, if we're already covered
1058 // by an earlier larger ShiftInwards split, there's no
1059 // point - it just complicates the IR and confuses bounds
1060 // inference. An example of this is:
1061 //
1062 // f.vectorize(x, 8).unroll(x, 4);
1063 //
1064 // The vectorize-induced split is ShiftInwards. There's no
1065 // point also applying ShiftInwards to the unroll-induced
1066 // split.
1067 //
1068 // Note that we'll still partition the outermost loop to
1069 // avoid the overhead of the min we placed in the inner
1070 // loop with the vectorize, because that's how loop
1071 // partitioning works. The steady-state will be just as
1072 // efficient as:
1073 //
1074 // f.split(x, x, xi, 32).vectorize(xi, 8).unroll(xi);
1075 //
1076 // It's only the tail/epilogue that changes.
1077
1078 std::map<string, Expr> descends_from_shiftinwards_outer;
1079 for (const Split &s : definition.schedule().splits()) {
1080 auto it = descends_from_shiftinwards_outer.find(s.old_var);
1081 if (s.is_split() && s.tail == TailStrategy::ShiftInwards) {
1082 descends_from_shiftinwards_outer[s.outer] = s.factor;
1083 } else if (s.is_split() && it != descends_from_shiftinwards_outer.end()) {
1084 descends_from_shiftinwards_outer[s.inner] = it->second;
1085 descends_from_shiftinwards_outer[s.outer] = it->second;
1086 } else if ((s.is_rename() || s.is_purify()) &&
1087 it != descends_from_shiftinwards_outer.end()) {
1088 descends_from_shiftinwards_outer[s.outer] = it->second;
1089 }
1090 }
1091 auto it = descends_from_shiftinwards_outer.find(old_name);
1092 if (it != descends_from_shiftinwards_outer.end() &&
1093 can_prove(it->second >= factor)) {
1094 tail = TailStrategy::RoundUp;
1095 } else {
1096 tail = TailStrategy::ShiftInwards;
1097 }
1098 }
1099 }
1100
1101 if (!definition.is_init()) {
1102 user_assert(tail != TailStrategy::ShiftInwards)
1103 << "When splitting Var " << old_name
1104 << " ShiftInwards is not a legal tail strategy for update definitions, as"
1105 << " it may change the meaning of the algorithm\n";
1106 }
1107
1108 if (exact) {
1109 user_assert(tail == TailStrategy::GuardWithIf || tail == TailStrategy::Predicate)
1110 << "When splitting Var " << old_name
1111 << " the tail strategy must be GuardWithIf, Predicate or Auto. "
1112 << "Anything else may change the meaning of the algorithm\n";
1113 }
1114
1115 // Add the split to the splits list
1116 Split split = {old_name, outer_name, inner_name, factor, exact, tail, Split::SplitVar};
1117 definition.schedule().splits().push_back(split);
1118}
1119
1120Stage &Stage::split(const VarOrRVar &old, const VarOrRVar &outer, const VarOrRVar &inner, const Expr &factor, TailStrategy tail) {
1121 if (old.is_rvar) {
1122 user_assert(outer.is_rvar) << "Can't split RVar " << old.name() << " into Var " << outer.name() << "\n";
1123 user_assert(inner.is_rvar) << "Can't split RVar " << old.name() << " into Var " << inner.name() << "\n";
1124 } else {
1125 user_assert(!outer.is_rvar) << "Can't split Var " << old.name() << " into RVar " << outer.name() << "\n";
1126 user_assert(!inner.is_rvar) << "Can't split Var " << old.name() << " into RVar " << inner.name() << "\n";
1127 }
1128 split(old.name(), outer.name(), inner.name(), factor, old.is_rvar, tail);
1129 return *this;
1130}
1131
1132Stage &Stage::fuse(const VarOrRVar &inner, const VarOrRVar &outer, const VarOrRVar &fused) {
1133 if (!fused.is_rvar) {
1134 user_assert(!outer.is_rvar) << "Can't fuse Var " << fused.name()
1135 << " from RVar " << outer.name() << "\n";
1136 user_assert(!inner.is_rvar) << "Can't fuse Var " << inner.name()
1137 << " from RVar " << inner.name() << "\n";
1138 }
1139
1140 debug(4) << "In schedule for " << name() << ", fuse " << outer.name()
1141 << " and " << inner.name() << " into " << fused.name() << "\n";
1142
1143 // Replace the old dimensions with the new dimension in the dims list
1144 bool found_outer = false, found_inner = false;
1145 string inner_name, outer_name, fused_name;
1146 vector<Dim> &dims = definition.schedule().dims();
1147
1148 DimType outer_type = DimType::PureRVar;
1149 for (size_t i = 0; (!found_outer) && i < dims.size(); i++) {
1150 if (var_name_match(dims[i].var, outer.name())) {
1151 found_outer = true;
1152 outer_name = dims[i].var;
1153 outer_type = dims[i].dim_type;
1154 dims.erase(dims.begin() + i);
1155 }
1156 }
1157 if (!found_outer) {
1158 user_error << "In schedule for " << name()
1159 << ", could not find outer fuse dimension: "
1160 << outer.name()
1161 << "\n"
1162 << dump_argument_list();
1163 }
1164
1165 for (size_t i = 0; (!found_inner) && i < dims.size(); i++) {
1166 if (var_name_match(dims[i].var, inner.name())) {
1167 found_inner = true;
1168 inner_name = dims[i].var;
1169 fused_name = inner_name + "." + fused.name();
1170 dims[i].var = fused_name;
1171
1172 if (dims[i].dim_type == DimType::ImpureRVar ||
1173 outer_type == DimType::ImpureRVar) {
1174 dims[i].dim_type = DimType::ImpureRVar;
1175 } else if (dims[i].dim_type == DimType::PureRVar ||
1176 outer_type == DimType::PureRVar) {
1177 dims[i].dim_type = DimType::PureRVar;
1178 } else {
1179 dims[i].dim_type = DimType::PureVar;
1180 }
1181 }
1182 }
1183
1184 if (!found_inner) {
1185 user_error << "In schedule for " << name()
1186 << ", could not find inner fuse dimension: "
1187 << inner.name()
1188 << "\n"
1189 << dump_argument_list();
1190 }
1191
1192 // Add the fuse to the splits list
1193 Split split = {fused_name, outer_name, inner_name, Expr(), true, TailStrategy::RoundUp, Split::FuseVars};
1194 definition.schedule().splits().push_back(split);
1195 return *this;
1196}

1198namespace Internal {
1199class CheckForFreeVars : public IRGraphVisitor {
1200public:
1201 string offending_var;
1202
1203protected:
1204 using IRGraphVisitor::visit;
1205 void visit(const Variable *var) override {
1206 if (!var->param.defined() && !var->image.defined()) {
1207 offending_var = var->name;
1208 }
1209 }
1210};
1211} // namespace Internal
1212
1213Stage Stage::specialize(const Expr &condition) {
1214 user_assert(condition.type().is_bool()) << "Argument passed to specialize must be of type bool\n";
1215
1216 // The condition may not depend on Vars or RVars
1217 Internal::CheckForFreeVars check;
1218 condition.accept(&check);
1219 if (!check.offending_var.empty()) {
1220 user_error << "Specialization condition " << condition << " for " << name()
1221 << " depends on Var or RVar " << check.offending_var << ". "
1222 << "Specialization conditions may not depend on any Vars or RVars.\n";
1223 }
1224
1225 // The user may be retrieving a reference to an existing
1226 // specialization.
1227 const vector<Specialization> &specializations = definition.specializations();
1228 for (const auto &specialization : specializations) {
1229 if (equal(condition, specialization.condition)) {
1230 return Stage(function, specialization.definition, stage_index);
1231 }
1232 }
1233
1234 // Can't add any more specializations after specialize_fail().
1235 user_assert(specializations.empty() || specializations.back().failure_message.empty())
1236 << "Cannot add new specializations after specialize_fail().";
1237 const Specialization &s = definition.add_specialization(condition);
1238
1239 return Stage(function, s.definition, stage_index);
1240}
1241
1242void Stage::specialize_fail(const std::string &message) {
1243 user_assert(!message.empty()) << "Argument passed to specialize_fail() must not be empty.\n";
1244 const vector<Specialization> &specializations = definition.specializations();
1245 user_assert(specializations.empty() || specializations.back().failure_message.empty())
1246 << "Only one specialize_fail() may be defined per Stage.";
1247 (void)definition.add_specialization(const_true());
1248 Specialization &s = definition.specializations().back();
1249 s.failure_message = message;
1250}

1252Stage &Stage::purify(const VarOrRVar &old_var, const VarOrRVar &new_var) {
1253 user_assert(old_var.is_rvar && !new_var.is_rvar)
1254 << "In schedule for " << name()
1255 << ", can't rename " << (old_var.is_rvar ? "RVar " : "Var ") << old_var.name()
1256 << " to " << (new_var.is_rvar ? "RVar " : "Var ") << new_var.name()
1257 << "; purify must take a RVar as old_Var and a Var as new_var\n";
1258
1259 debug(4) << "In schedule for " << name() << ", purify RVar "
1260 << old_var.name() << " to Var " << new_var.name() << "\n";
1261
1262 StageSchedule &schedule = definition.schedule();
1263
1264 // Replace the old dimension with the new dimensions in the dims list
1265 bool found = false;
1266 string old_name, new_name = new_var.name();
1267 vector<Dim> &dims = schedule.dims();
1268
1269 for (size_t i = 0; (!found) && i < dims.size(); i++) {
1270 if (var_name_match(dims[i].var, old_var.name())) {
1271 found = true;
1272 old_name = dims[i].var;
1273 dims[i].var = new_name;
1274 dims[i].dim_type = DimType::PureVar;
1275 }
1276 }
1277
1278 if (!found) {
1279 user_error
1280 << "In schedule for " << name()
1281 << ", could not find rename dimension: "
1282 << old_var.name()
1283 << "\n"
1284 << dump_argument_list();
1285 }
1286
1287 Split split = {old_name, new_name, "", 1, false, TailStrategy::RoundUp, Split::PurifyRVar};
1288 definition.schedule().splits().push_back(split);
1289 return *this;
1290}
1291
1292void Stage::remove(const string &var) {
1293 debug(4) << "In schedule for " << name() << ", remove " << var << "\n";
1294
1295 StageSchedule &schedule = definition.schedule();
1296
1297 // Replace the old dimension with the new dimensions in the dims list
1298 bool found = false;
1299 string old_name = var;
1300 vector<Dim> &dims = schedule.dims();
1301 for (size_t i = 0; (!found) && i < dims.size(); i++) {
1302 if (dims[i].var == var) {
1303 found = true;
1304 old_name = dims[i].var;
1305 dims.erase(dims.begin() + i);
1306 }
1307 }
1308
1309 if (!found) {
1310 user_error
1311 << "In schedule for " << name()
1312 << ", could not find remove dimension: "
1313 << var
1314 << "\n"
1315 << dump_argument_list();
1316 }
1317
1318 std::set<string> removed_vars;
1319 removed_vars.insert(var);
1320
1321 auto should_remove = [&removed_vars](const string &var) {
1322 const auto &iter = std::find_if(
1323 removed_vars.begin(), removed_vars.end(), [&var](const string &rv) { return rv == var; });
1324 return iter != removed_vars.end();
1325 };
1326
1327 vector<Split> &splits = schedule.splits();
1328 vector<Split> temp;
1329 for (size_t i = splits.size(); i > 0; i--) {
1330 bool is_removed = false;
1331 if (splits[i - 1].is_fuse()) {
1332 debug(4) << " checking fuse " << splits[i - 1].inner << " and "
1333 << splits[i - 1].inner << " into " << splits[i - 1].old_var << "\n";
1334 if (splits[i - 1].inner == old_name ||
1335 splits[i - 1].outer == old_name) {
1336 user_error
1337 << "In schedule for " << name()
1338 << ", can't remove variable " << old_name
1339 << " because it has already been fused into "
1340 << splits[i - 1].old_var << "\n"
1341 << dump_argument_list();
1342 }
1343 if (should_remove(splits[i - 1].old_var)) {
1344 is_removed = true;
1345 removed_vars.insert(splits[i - 1].outer);
1346 removed_vars.insert(splits[i - 1].inner);
1347 }
1348 } else if (splits[i - 1].is_split()) {
1349 debug(4) << " splitting " << splits[i - 1].old_var << " into "
1350 << splits[i - 1].outer << " and " << splits[i - 1].inner << "\n";
1351 if (should_remove(splits[i - 1].inner)) {
1352 is_removed = true;
1353 removed_vars.insert(splits[i - 1].old_var);
1354 } else if (should_remove(splits[i - 1].outer)) {
1355 is_removed = true;
1356 removed_vars.insert(splits[i - 1].old_var);
1357 }
1358 if (splits[i - 1].old_var == old_name) {
1359 user_error
1360 << "In schedule for " << name()
1361 << ", can't remove a variable " << old_name
1362 << " because it has already been renamed or split.\n"
1363 << dump_argument_list();
1364 }
1365 } else {
1366 debug(4) << " replace/rename " << splits[i - 1].old_var
1367 << " into " << splits[i - 1].outer << "\n";
1368 if (should_remove(splits[i - 1].outer)) {
1369 is_removed = true;
1370 removed_vars.insert(splits[i - 1].old_var);
1371 }
1372 if (splits[i - 1].old_var == old_name) {
1373 user_error
1374 << "In schedule for " << name()
1375 << ", can't remove a variable " << old_name
1376 << " because it has already been renamed or split.\n"
1377 << dump_argument_list();
1378 }
1379 }
1380 if (!is_removed) {
1381 temp.insert(temp.begin(), splits[i - 1]);
1382 }
1383 }
1384 splits.swap(temp);
1385}
1386
1387Stage &Stage::rename(const VarOrRVar &old_var, const VarOrRVar &new_var) {
1388 if (old_var.is_rvar) {
1389 user_assert(new_var.is_rvar)
1390 << "In schedule for " << name()
1391 << ", can't rename RVar " << old_var.name()
1392 << " to Var " << new_var.name() << "\n";
1393 } else {
1394 user_assert(!new_var.is_rvar)
1395 << "In schedule for " << name()
1396 << ", can't rename Var " << old_var.name()
1397 << " to RVar " << new_var.name() << "\n";
1398 }
1399
1400 debug(4) << "In schedule for " << name() << ", rename " << old_var.name()
1401 << " to " << new_var.name() << "\n";
1402
1403 StageSchedule &schedule = definition.schedule();
1404
1405 // Replace the old dimension with the new dimensions in the dims list
1406 bool found = false;
1407 string old_name;
1408 vector<Dim> &dims = schedule.dims();
1409 for (size_t i = 0; (!found) && i < dims.size(); i++) {
1410 if (var_name_match(dims[i].var, old_var.name())) {
1411 found = true;
1412 old_name = dims[i].var;
1413 dims[i].var += "." + new_var.name();
1414 }
1415 }
1416
1417 string new_name = old_name + "." + new_var.name();
1418
1419 if (!found) {
1420 user_error
1421 << "In schedule for " << name()
1422 << ", could not find rename dimension: "
1423 << old_var.name()
1424 << "\n"
1425 << dump_argument_list();
1426 }
1427
1428 // If possible, rewrite the split or rename that defines it.
1429 found = false;
1430 vector<Split> &splits = schedule.splits();
1431 for (size_t i = splits.size(); i > 0; i--) {
1432 if (splits[i - 1].is_fuse()) {
1433 if (splits[i - 1].inner == old_name ||
1434 splits[i - 1].outer == old_name) {
1435 user_error
1436 << "In schedule for " << name()
1437 << ", can't rename variable " << old_name
1438 << " because it has already been fused into "
1439 << splits[i - 1].old_var << "\n"
1440 << dump_argument_list();
1441 }
1442 if (splits[i - 1].old_var == old_name) {
1443 splits[i - 1].old_var = new_name;
1444 found = true;
1445 break;
1446 }
1447 } else {
1448 if (splits[i - 1].inner == old_name) {
1449 splits[i - 1].inner = new_name;
1450 found = true;
1451 break;
1452 }
1453 if (splits[i - 1].outer == old_name) {
1454 splits[i - 1].outer = new_name;
1455 found = true;
1456 break;
1457 }
1458 if (splits[i - 1].old_var == old_name) {
1459 user_error
1460 << "In schedule for " << name()
1461 << ", can't rename a variable " << old_name
1462 << " because it has already been renamed or split.\n"
1463 << dump_argument_list();
1464 }
1465 }
1466 }
1467
1468 if (!found) {
1469 Split split = {old_name, new_name, "", 1, old_var.is_rvar, TailStrategy::RoundUp, Split::RenameVar};
1470 definition.schedule().splits().push_back(split);
1471 }
1472
1473 return *this;
1474}

1567Stage &Stage::tile(const std::vector<VarOrRVar> &previous,
1568 const std::vector<VarOrRVar> &outers,
1569 const std::vector<VarOrRVar> &inners,
1570 const std::vector<Expr> &factors,
1571 const std::vector<TailStrategy> &tails) {
1572 if (previous.size() != outers.size() || previous.size() != inners.size() || previous.size() != factors.size() || previous.size() != tails.size()) {
1573 user_error << "Vectors passed to Stage::tile must all be the same length.\n";
1574 }
1575 for (unsigned int i = 0; i < previous.size(); i++) {
1576 split(previous[i], outers[i], inners[i], factors[i], tails[i]);
1577 }
1578 std::vector<VarOrRVar> new_order;
1579 new_order.insert(new_order.end(), inners.begin(), inners.end());
1580 new_order.insert(new_order.end(), outers.begin(), outers.end());
1581 reorder(new_order);
1582 return *this;
1583}

1585Stage &Stage::tile(const std::vector<VarOrRVar> &previous,
1586 const std::vector<VarOrRVar> &outers,
1587 const std::vector<VarOrRVar> &inners,
1588 const std::vector<Expr> &factors,
1589 TailStrategy tail) {
1590 std::vector<TailStrategy> tails;
1591 for (unsigned int i = 0; i < previous.size(); i++) {
1592 tails.push_back(tail);
1593 }
1594 return tile(previous, outers, inners, factors, tails);
1595}

1603
1604Stage &Stage::reorder(const std::vector<VarOrRVar> &vars) {
1605 const string &func_name = function.name();
1606 vector<Expr> &args = definition.args();
1607 vector<Expr> &values = definition.values();
1608 vector<Dim> &dims_old = definition.schedule().dims();
1609 vector<Dim> dims = dims_old;
1610
1611 // Tag all the vars with their locations in the dims list.
1612 vector<size_t> idx(vars.size());
1613 for (size_t i = 0; i < vars.size(); i++) {
1614 bool found = false;
1615 for (size_t j = 0; j < dims.size(); j++) {
1616 if (var_name_match(dims[j].var, vars[i].name())) {
1617 idx[i] = j;
1618 found = true;
1619 }
1620 }
1621 user_assert(found)
1622 << "In schedule for " << name()
1623 << ", could not find var " << vars[i].name()
1624 << " to reorder in the argument list.\n"
1625 << dump_argument_list();
1626 // Check for duplicates
1627 for (size_t j = 0; j < i; j++) {
1628 user_assert(idx[i] != idx[j])
1629 << "In schedule for " << name()
1630 << ", call to reorder references " << vars[i].name()
1631 << " twice.\n";
1632 }
1633 }
1634
1635 // It is illegal to reorder RVars if the stage is not associative
1636 // or not commutative. Look for RVar reorderings and try to do the
1637 // necessary proof if any are found.
1638 bool safe_to_reorder = is_const_assignment(func_name, args, values);
1639 for (size_t i = 0; !safe_to_reorder && i < idx.size(); i++) {
1640 if (!dims[idx[i]].is_pure()) {
1641 for (size_t j = i + 1; !safe_to_reorder && j < idx.size(); j++) {
1642 if (!dims[idx[j]].is_pure() && (idx[i] > idx[j])) {
1643 // Generate an error if the operator is not both associative and commutative.
1644 const auto &prover_result = prove_associativity(func_name, args, values);
1645 safe_to_reorder = prover_result.associative() &&
1646 prover_result.commutative();
1647 if (!safe_to_reorder) {
1648 user_error
1649 << "In schedule for " << name()
1650 << ", can't reorder RVars " << vars[i].name()
1651 << " and " << vars[j].name()
1652 << " because it may change the meaning of the "
1653 << "algorithm.\n";
1654 }
1655 }
1656 }
1657 }
1658 }
1659
1660 // Sort idx to get the new locations
1661 vector<size_t> sorted = idx;
1662 std::sort(sorted.begin(), sorted.end());
1663
1664 for (size_t i = 0; i < vars.size(); i++) {
1665 dims[sorted[i]] = dims_old[idx[i]];
1666 }
1667
1668 dims_old.swap(dims);
1669
1670 return *this;
1671}

1797Stage &Stage::gpu_tile(const VarOrRVar &x, const VarOrRVar &y, const VarOrRVar &z,

1819 set_dim_device_api(tz, device_api);

1822 set_dim_type(by, ForType::GPUBlock);
1823 set_dim_type(bz, ForType::GPUBlock);
1824 set_dim_type(tx, ForType::GPUThread);
1825 set_dim_type(ty, ForType::GPUThread);
1826 set_dim_type(tz, ForType::GPUThread);

1855Stage &Stage::compute_with(LoopLevel loop_level, const map<string, LoopAlignStrategy> &align) {
1856 loop_level.lock();
1857 user_assert(!loop_level.is_inlined() && !loop_level.is_root())
1858 << "Undefined loop level to compute with\n";
1859 user_assert(loop_level.func() != function.name())
1860 << "Cannot schedule " << name() << " to be computed with "
1861 << loop_level.to_string() << "\n";
1862 user_assert(!function.has_extern_definition())
1863 << "compute_with() on extern Func " << name() << " is not allowed\n";
1864
1865 // We have to mark the fuse level on the "original" definition (the one
1866 // without the specialization) to ensure there is no competing compute_with.
1867 Definition &original_def = (stage_index == 0) ? function.definition() : function.update(stage_index - 1);
1868 user_assert(original_def.specializations().empty())
1869 << "Func " << name() << " is scheduled to be computed with "
1870 << loop_level.func() << ", so it must not have any specializations.\n";
1871
1872 FuseLoopLevel &fuse_level = original_def.schedule().fuse_level();
1873 if (!fuse_level.level.lock().is_inlined()) {
1874 user_warning << name() << " already has a compute_with at " << fuse_level.level.to_string()
1875 << ". Replacing it with a new compute_with at " << loop_level.to_string() << "\n";
1876 }
1877 fuse_level.level = loop_level;
1878 fuse_level.align = align;
1879 return *this;
1880}
1881
1882Stage &Stage::compute_with(LoopLevel loop_level, const vector<pair<VarOrRVar, LoopAlignStrategy>> &align) {
1883 map<string, LoopAlignStrategy> align_str;
1884 for (const auto &iter : align) {
1885 align_str.emplace(iter.first.name(), iter.second);
1886 }
1887 return compute_with(std::move(loop_level), align_str);
1888}
1889
1890Stage &Stage::compute_with(LoopLevel loop_level, LoopAlignStrategy align) {
1891 map<string, LoopAlignStrategy> align_str = {{loop_level.lock().var().name(), align}};
1892 return compute_with(loop_level, align_str);
1893}
1894
1895Stage &Stage::compute_with(const Stage &s, const VarOrRVar &var, const vector<pair<VarOrRVar, LoopAlignStrategy>> &align) {
1896 return compute_with(LoopLevel(s.function, var, s.stage_index), align);
1897}

1900 return compute_with(LoopLevel(s.function, var, s.stage_index), align);

1919void validate_wrapper(const string &name, const map<string, FunctionPtr> &wrappers,
1920 const vector<Func> &fs, const FunctionPtr &wrapper) {
1921 if (!wrappers.empty() && !fs.empty()) {
1922 internal_assert(wrapper.defined() && !name.empty());
1923 // Make sure all the other Funcs in 'fs' share the same wrapper and no
1924 // other Func not in 'fs' share the same wrapper
1925 for (const auto &it : wrappers) {
1926 if (it.first == fs[0].name()) {
1927 continue;
1928 }
1929 const auto &fs_iter = std::find_if(
1930 fs.begin(), fs.end(), [&it](const Func &f) { return f.name() == it.first; });
1931 bool in_fs = fs_iter != fs.end();
1932
1933 if (in_fs) {
1934 user_assert(it.second.same_as(wrapper))
1935 << it.first << " should have shared the same wrapper as " << fs[0].name() << "\n";
1936 } else {
1937 user_assert(!it.second.same_as(wrapper))
1938 << "Redefinition of shared wrapper [" << name << " -> "
1939 << Function(wrapper).name() << "] in " << fs[0].name() << " is illegal since "
1940 << it.first << " shares the same wrapper but is not part of the redefinition\n";
1941 }
1942 }
1943 }
1944}
1945
1946Func create_in_wrapper(Function wrapped_fn, const string &wrapper_name) {
1947 Func wrapper(wrapped_fn.new_function_in_same_group(wrapper_name));
1948 vector<Var> args = Func(wrapped_fn).args();
1949 wrapper(args) = Func(wrapped_fn)(args);
1950 return wrapper;
1951}
1952
1953Func create_clone_wrapper(Function wrapped_fn, const string &wrapper_name) {
1954 Func wrapper(wrapped_fn.new_function_in_same_group(wrapper_name));
1955 std::map<FunctionPtr, FunctionPtr> remapping;
1956 wrapped_fn.deep_copy(wrapper.name(), wrapper.function().get_contents(), remapping);
1957 // Fix up any self-references in the clone.
1958 FunctionPtr self_reference = wrapper.function().get_contents();
1959 self_reference.weaken();
1960 remapping.emplace(wrapped_fn.get_contents(), self_reference);
1961 wrapper.function().substitute_calls(remapping);
1962 return wrapper;
1963}
1964
1965Func get_wrapper(Function wrapped_fn, string wrapper_name, const vector<Func> &fs, bool clone) {
1966 // Either all Funcs in 'fs' have the same wrapper or they don't already
1967 // have any wrappers. Otherwise, throw an error. If 'fs' is empty, then
1968 // it is a global wrapper.
1969 const map<string, FunctionPtr> &wrappers = wrapped_fn.wrappers();
1970 wrapper_name += ("$" + std::to_string(wrappers.size()));
1971 const auto &iter = fs.empty() ? wrappers.find("") : wrappers.find(fs[0].name());
1972 if (iter == wrappers.end()) {
1973 // Make sure the other Funcs also don't have any wrappers
1974 for (size_t i = 1; i < fs.size(); ++i) {
1975 user_assert(wrappers.count(fs[i].name()) == 0)
1976 << "Cannot define the wrapper since " << fs[i].name()
1977 << " already has a wrapper while " << fs[0].name() << " doesn't \n";
1978 }
1979 Func wrapper = clone ? create_clone_wrapper(wrapped_fn, wrapper_name) : create_in_wrapper(wrapped_fn, wrapper_name);
1980 Function wrapper_fn = wrapper.function();
1981 if (fs.empty()) {
1982 // Add global wrapper
1983 wrapped_fn.add_wrapper("", wrapper_fn);
1984 } else {
1985 for (const Func &f : fs) {
1986 user_assert(wrapped_fn.name() != f.name())
1987 << "Cannot create wrapper of itself (\"" << wrapped_fn.name() << "\")\n";
1988 wrapped_fn.add_wrapper(f.name(), wrapper_fn);
1989 }
1990 }
1991 return wrapper;
1992 }
1993 internal_assert(iter->second.defined());
1994 validate_wrapper(wrapped_fn.name(), wrappers, fs, iter->second);
1995
1996 Function wrapper(iter->second);
1997 internal_assert(wrapper.frozen());
1998 return Func(wrapper);
1999}
2000
2001} // anonymous namespace

2007}

2036Func Func::copy_to_device(DeviceAPI d) {
2037 user_assert(defined())
2038 << "copy_to_device on Func " << name() << " with no definition\n";
2039 user_assert(outputs() == 1)
2040 << "copy_to_device on a Tuple-valued Func " << name() << " not yet supported\n";
2041 user_assert(!has_update_definition())
2042 << "copy_to_device on Func " << name() << " with update definition\n";
2043 user_assert(!is_extern())
2044 << "copy_to_device on Func " << name() << " with extern definition\n";
2045
2046 const Call *call = func.is_wrapper();
2047 user_assert(call)
2048 << "Func " << name() << " is scheduled as copy_to_host/device, "
2049 << "but has value: " << value() << "\n"
2050 << "Expected a single call to another Func with matching "
2051 << "dimensionality and argument order.\n";
2052
2053 // Move the RHS value to the proxy slot
2054 func.extern_definition_proxy_expr() = value();
2055
2056 // ... and delete the pure definition
2057 func.definition() = Definition();
2058
2059 ExternFuncArgument buffer;
2060 if (call->call_type == Call::Halide) {
2061 buffer = call->func;
2062 } else if (call->image.defined()) {
2063 buffer = call->image;
2064 } else {
2065 internal_assert(call->param.defined());
2066 buffer = call->param;
2067 }
2068
2069 ExternFuncArgument device_interface = make_device_interface_call(d);
2070 func.define_extern("halide_buffer_copy", {buffer, device_interface},
2071 {call->type}, args(), // Reuse the existing dimension names
2072 NameMangling::C, d);
2073 return *this;
2074}

2076Func Func::copy_to_host() {
2077 user_assert(defined())
2078 << "copy_to_host on Func " << name() << " with no definition\n";
2079 user_assert(outputs() == 1)
2080 << "copy_to_host on a Tuple-valued Func " << name() << " not yet supported\n";
2081 user_assert(!has_update_definition())
2082 << "copy_to_host on Func " << name() << " with update definition\n";
2083 user_assert(!is_extern())
2084 << "copy_to_host on Func " << name() << " with extern definition\n";
2085 return copy_to_device(DeviceAPI::Host);
2086}

2118Func &Func::memoize(const EvictionKey &eviction_key) {
2119 invalidate_cache();
2120 func.schedule().memoized() = true;
2121 if (eviction_key.key.defined()) {
2122 Expr new_eviction_key;
2123 const Type &t(eviction_key.key.type());
2124 if (!t.is_scalar()) {
2125 user_error << "Can't use a vector as a memoization eviction key. Expression is: "
2126 << eviction_key.key << "\n";
2127 }
2128 if (t.is_float()) {
2129 user_error << "Can't use floating-point types as a memoization eviction key. Expression is: "
2130 << eviction_key.key << "\n";
2131 } else if (t.is_handle()) {
2132 // Wrap this in a memoize_tag so it does not get used in
2133 // the cache key. Would be nice to have void version of
2134 // memoize_tag that adds no bits to the key, but that is a
2135 // small optimization.
2136 new_eviction_key = memoize_tag(reinterpret(UInt(64), eviction_key.key), 0);
2137 } else {
2138 // Ditto above re: memoize_tag
2139 new_eviction_key = memoize_tag(reinterpret(UInt(64), cast(t.with_bits(64),
2140 eviction_key.key)),
2141 0);
2142 }
2143
2144 if (func.schedule().memoize_eviction_key().defined() &&
2145 !graph_equal(func.schedule().memoize_eviction_key(), eviction_key.key)) {
2146 user_error << "Can't redefine memoize eviction key. First definition is: "
2147 << func.schedule().memoize_eviction_key()
2148 << " new definition is: " << new_eviction_key << "\n";
2149 }
2150
2151 func.schedule().memoize_eviction_key() = new_eviction_key;
2152 } else {
2153 func.schedule().memoize_eviction_key() = eviction_key.key; // not defined.
2154 }
2155 return *this;
2156}

2222Func &Func::bound(const Var &var, Expr min, Expr extent) {
2223 user_assert(!min.defined() || Int(32).can_represent(min.type())) << "Can't represent min bound in int32\n";
2224 user_assert(extent.defined()) << "Extent bound of a Func can't be undefined\n";
2225 user_assert(Int(32).can_represent(extent.type())) << "Can't represent extent bound in int32\n";
2226
2227 if (min.defined()) {
2228 min = cast<int32_t>(min);
2229 }
2230 extent = cast<int32_t>(extent);
2231
2232 invalidate_cache();
2233 bool found = func.is_pure_arg(var.name());
2234 user_assert(found)
2235 << "Can't bound variable " << var.name()
2236 << " of function " << name()
2237 << " because " << var.name()
2238 << " is not one of the pure variables of " << name() << ".\n";
2239
2240 Bound b = {var.name(), min, extent, Expr(), Expr()};
2241 func.schedule().bounds().push_back(b);
2242
2243 // Propagate constant bounds into estimates as well.
2244 if (!is_const(min)) {
2245 min = Expr();
2246 }
2247 if (!is_const(extent)) {
2248 extent = Expr();
2249 }
2250 set_estimate(var, min, extent);
2251
2252 return *this;
2253}
2254
2255Func &Func::set_estimate(const Var &var, const Expr &min, const Expr &extent) {
2256 invalidate_cache();
2257 bool found = func.is_pure_arg(var.name());
2258 user_assert(found)
2259 << "Can't provide an estimate on variable " << var.name()
2260 << " of function " << name()
2261 << " because " << var.name()
2262 << " is not one of the pure variables of " << name() << ".\n";
2263
2264 Bound b = {var.name(), min, extent, Expr(), Expr()};
2265 func.schedule().estimates().push_back(b);
2266
2267 // Propagate the estimate into the Parameter as well, so that
2268 // the values in the metadata will be correct.
2269 const auto &arg_names = func.args();
2270 int dim = -1;
2271 for (size_t i = 0; i < arg_names.size(); ++i) {
2272 if (arg_names[i] == var.name()) {
2273 dim = i;
2274 break;
2275 }
2276 }
2277 internal_assert(dim >= 0);
2278 for (auto param : func.output_buffers()) {
2279 if (min.defined()) {
2280 param.set_min_constraint_estimate(dim, min);
2281 }
2282 if (extent.defined()) {
2283 param.set_extent_constraint_estimate(dim, extent);
2284 }
2285 }
2286 return *this;
2287}
2288
2289Func &Func::set_estimates(const Region &estimates) {
2290 const std::vector<Var> a = args();
2291 user_assert(estimates.size() == a.size())
2292 << "Func " << name() << " has " << a.size() << " dimensions, "
2293 << "but the estimates passed to set_estimates contains " << estimates.size() << " pairs.\n";
2294 for (size_t i = 0; i < a.size(); i++) {
2295 const Range &r = estimates[i];
2296 set_estimate(a[i], r.min, r.extent);
2297 }
2298 return *this;
2299}

2543Func &Func::reorder_storage(const Var &x, const Var &y) {
2544 invalidate_cache();
2545
2546 user_assert(x.name() != y.name())
2547 << "In schedule for " << name()
2548 << ", call to reorder_storage references "
2549 << x.name() << " twice\n";
2550
2551 vector<StorageDim> &dims = func.schedule().storage_dims();
2552 bool found_y = false;
2553 size_t y_loc = 0;
2554 for (size_t i = 0; i < dims.size(); i++) {
2555 if (var_name_match(dims[i].var, y.name())) {
2556 found_y = true;
2557 y_loc = i;
2558 } else if (var_name_match(dims[i].var, x.name())) {
2559 if (found_y) {
2560 std::swap(dims[i], dims[y_loc]);
2561 }
2562 return *this;
2563 }
2564 }
2565 user_error << "In schedule for " << name()
2566 << ", could not find variables " << x.name()
2567 << " and " << y.name() << " to reorder.\n"
2568 << dump_dim_list(dims);
2569 return *this;
2570}
2571
2572Func &Func::reorder_storage(const std::vector<Var> &dims, size_t start) {
2573 // Reorder the first dimension with respect to all others, then
2574 // recursively reorder all remaining dimensions.
2575 for (size_t i = start + 1; i < dims.size(); i++) {
2576 reorder_storage(dims[start], dims[i]);
2577 }
2578 if ((dims.size() - start) > 2) {
2579 reorder_storage(dims, start + 1);
2580 }
2581 return *this;
2582}
2583
2584Func &Func::reorder_storage(const std::vector<Var> &dims) {
2585 user_assert(dims.size() > 1) << "reorder_storage must have at least two dimensions in reorder list.\n";
2586
2587 return reorder_storage(dims, 0);
2588}

2735namespace {
2736class CountImplicitVars : public Internal::IRGraphVisitor {
2737public:
2738 int count;
2739
2740 CountImplicitVars(const vector<Expr> &e)
2741 : count(0) {
2742 for (size_t i = 0; i < e.size(); i++) {
2743 e[i].accept(this);
2744 }
2745 }
2746
2747 using IRGraphVisitor::visit;
2748
2749 void visit(const Variable *v) override {
2750 int index = Var::implicit_index(v->name);
2751 if (index != -1) {
2752 if (index >= count) {
2753 count = index + 1;
2754 }
2755 }
2756 }
2757};
2758} // namespace
2759
2760FuncRef::FuncRef(const Internal::Function &f, const vector<Expr> &a, int placeholder_pos,
2761 int count)
2762 : func(f), implicit_count(count), args(a) {
2763 implicit_placeholder_pos = placeholder_pos;
2764 Internal::check_call_arg_types(f.name(), &args, args.size());
2765}
2766
2767FuncRef::FuncRef(Internal::Function f, const vector<Var> &a, int placeholder_pos,
2768 int count)
2769 : func(std::move(f)), implicit_count(count) {
2770 implicit_placeholder_pos = placeholder_pos;
2771 args.resize(a.size());
2772 for (size_t i = 0; i < a.size(); i++) {
2773 args[i] = a[i];
2774 }
2775}
2776
2777vector<Expr> FuncRef::args_with_implicit_vars(const vector<Expr> &e) const {
2778 vector<Expr> a = args;
2779
2780 for (size_t i = 0; i < a.size(); i++) {
2781 user_assert(a[i].defined())
2782 << "Argument " << (i + 1) << " in call to \"" << func.name() << "\" is undefined.\n";
2783 }
2784 for (size_t i = 0; i < e.size(); i++) {
2785 user_assert(e[i].defined())
2786 << "Value " << (i + 1) << " in definition of \"" << func.name() << "\" is undefined.\n";
2787 }
2788
2789 CountImplicitVars count(e);
2790 for (size_t i = 0; i < a.size(); i++) {
2791 a[i].accept(&count);
2792 }
2793
2794 if (count.count > 0) {
2795 if (func.has_pure_definition()) {
2796 // If the func already has pure definition, the number of implicit
2797 // vars in the RHS can only be at most the number of implicit vars
2798 // in the LHS.
2799 user_assert(implicit_count >= count.count)
2800 << "The update definition of " << func.name() << " uses " << count.count
2801 << " implicit variables, but the initial definition uses only "
2802 << implicit_count << " implicit variables.\n";
2803 } else if (implicit_placeholder_pos != -1) {
2804 internal_assert(implicit_count == 0)
2805 << "Pure definition can't possibly already have implicit variables defined\n";
2806
2807 Internal::debug(2) << "Adding " << count.count << " implicit vars to LHS of " << func.name() << "\n";
2808
2809 vector<Expr>::iterator iter = a.begin() + implicit_placeholder_pos;
2810 for (int i = 0; i < count.count; i++) {
2811 iter = a.insert(iter, Var::implicit(i));
2812 iter++;
2813 }
2814 }
2815 }
2816
2817 // Check the implicit vars in the RHS also exist in the LHS
2818 for (int i = 0; i < count.count; i++) {
2819 Var v = Var::implicit(i);
2820 bool found = false;
2821 for (size_t j = 0; j < a.size(); j++) {
2822 if (const Variable *arg = a[j].as<Variable>()) {
2823 if (arg->name == v.name()) {
2824 found = true;
2825 }
2826 }
2827 }
2828 user_assert(found)
2829 << "Right-hand-side of update definition of " << func.name()
2830 << " uses implicit variables, but the left-hand-side does not"
2831 << " contain the placeholder symbol '_'.\n";
2832 }
2833
2834 return a;
2835}
2836
2837Stage FuncRef::operator=(const Expr &e) {
2838 return (*this) = Tuple(e);
2839}
2840
2841Stage FuncRef::operator=(const Tuple &e) {
2842 if (!func.has_pure_definition()) {
2843 for (size_t i = 0; i < args.size(); ++i) {
2844 const Variable *var = args[i].as<Variable>();
2845 user_assert((var != nullptr) && (!var->reduction_domain.defined()))
2846 << "Argument " << (i + 1) << " in initial definition of \""
2847 << func.name() << "\" is not a Var.\n";
2848 }
2849
2850 // Find implicit args in the expr and add them to the args list before calling define
2851 vector<Expr> expanded_args = args_with_implicit_vars(e.as_vector());
2852 vector<string> expanded_args_str(expanded_args.size());
2853 for (size_t i = 0; i < expanded_args.size(); ++i) {
2854 const Variable *v = expanded_args[i].as<Variable>();
2855 internal_assert(v);
2856 expanded_args_str[i] = v->name;
2857 }
2858 func.define(expanded_args_str, e.as_vector());
2859 return Stage(func, func.definition(), 0);
2860 } else {
2861 func.define_update(args, e.as_vector());
2862
2863 size_t update_stage = func.updates().size() - 1;
2864 return Stage(func, func.update(update_stage), update_stage);
2865 }
2866}

2868Stage FuncRef::operator=(const FuncRef &e) {
2869 if (e.size() == 1) {
2870 return (*this) = Expr(e);
2871 } else {
2872 return (*this) = Tuple(e);
2873 }
2874}

2876// Inject a suitable base-case definition given an update
2877// definition. This is a helper for FuncRef::operator+= and co.
2878Func define_base_case(const Internal::Function &func, const vector<Expr> &a, const Tuple &e) {
2879 Func f(func);
2880
2881 if (func.has_pure_definition()) {
2882 return f;
2883 }
2884 vector<Var> pure_args(a.size());
2885
2886 // Reuse names of existing pure args
2887 for (size_t i = 0; i < a.size(); i++) {
2888 if (const Variable *v = a[i].as<Variable>()) {
2889 if (!v->param.defined()) {
2890 pure_args[i] = Var(v->name);
2891 }
2892 } else {
2893 pure_args[i] = Var();
2894 }
2895 }
2896
2897 f(pure_args) = e;
2898 return f;
2899}
2900
2901Func define_base_case(const Internal::Function &func, const vector<Expr> &a, const Expr &e) {
2902 return define_base_case(func, a, Tuple(e));
2903}
2904
2905template<typename BinaryOp>
2906Stage FuncRef::func_ref_update(const Tuple &e, int init_val) {
2907 internal_assert(e.size() > 1);
2908
2909 vector<Expr> init_values(e.size());
2910 for (int i = 0; i < (int)init_values.size(); ++i) {
2911 init_values[i] = cast(e[i].type(), init_val);
2912 }
2913 vector<Expr> expanded_args = args_with_implicit_vars(e.as_vector());
2914 FuncRef self_ref = define_base_case(func, expanded_args, Tuple(init_values))(expanded_args);
2915
2916 vector<Expr> values(e.size());
2917 for (int i = 0; i < (int)values.size(); ++i) {
2918 values[i] = BinaryOp()(self_ref[i], e[i]);
2919 }
2920 return self_ref = Tuple(values);
2921}
2922
2923template<typename BinaryOp>
2924Stage FuncRef::func_ref_update(Expr e, int init_val) {
2925 vector<Expr> expanded_args = args_with_implicit_vars({e});
2926 FuncRef self_ref = define_base_case(func, expanded_args, cast(e.type(), init_val))(expanded_args);
2927 return self_ref = BinaryOp()(Expr(self_ref), e);
2928}

2961
2962Stage FuncRef::operator*=(const FuncRef &e) {
2963 if (e.size() == 1) {

3010FuncRef::operator Expr() const {
3011 user_assert(func.has_pure_definition() || func.has_extern_definition())
3012 << "Can't call Func \"" << func.name() << "\" because it has not yet been defined.\n";
3013
3014 user_assert(func.outputs() == 1)
3015 << "Can't convert a reference Func \"" << func.name()
3016 << "\" to an Expr, because " << func.name() << " returns a Tuple.\n";

3021FuncTupleElementRef FuncRef::operator[](int i) const {
3022 user_assert(func.has_pure_definition() || func.has_extern_definition())
3023 << "Can't call Func \"" << func.name() << "\" because it has not yet been defined.\n";
3024

3047Tuple FuncTupleElementRef::values_with_undefs(const Expr &e) const {
3048 vector<Expr> values(func_ref.size());
3049 for (int i = 0; i < (int)values.size(); ++i) {
3050 if (i == idx) {
3051 values[i] = e;
3052 } else {
3053 Type t = func_ref.function().values()[i].type();
3054 values[i] = undef(t);
3055 }
3056 }
3057 return Tuple(values);
3058}
